24 /* Standard ELF types. */
25 
26 #include <stdint.h>
27 
28 /* Type for a 16-bit quantity. */
29 typedef uint16_t Elf32_Half;
30 typedef uint16_t Elf64_Half;
31 
32 /* Types for signed and unsigned 32-bit quantities. */
33 typedef uint32_t Elf32_Word;
34 typedef int32_t Elf32_Sword;
35 typedef uint32_t Elf64_Word;
36 typedef int32_t Elf64_Sword;
37 
38 /* Types for signed and unsigned 64-bit quantities. */
39 typedef uint64_t Elf32_Xword;
40 typedef int64_t Elf32_Sxword;
41 typedef uint64_t Elf64_Xword;
42 typedef int64_t Elf64_Sxword;
43 
44 /* Type of addresses. */
45 typedef uint32_t Elf32_Addr;
46 typedef uint64_t Elf64_Addr;
47 
48 /* Type of file offsets. */
49 typedef uint32_t Elf32_Off;
50 typedef uint64_t Elf64_Off;
51 
52 /* Type for section indices, which are 16-bit quantities. */
53 typedef uint16_t Elf32_Section;
54 typedef uint16_t Elf64_Section;
55 
56 /* Type for version symbol information. */
57 typedef Elf32_Half Elf32_Versym;
58 typedef Elf64_Half Elf64_Versym;

61 /* The ELF file header. This appears at the start of every ELF file. */
62 
63 #define EI_NIDENT (16)
64 
65 typedef struct
66 {
67  unsigned char e_ident[EI_NIDENT]; /* Magic number and other info */
68  Elf32_Half e_type; /* Object file type */
69  Elf32_Half e_machine; /* Architecture */
70  Elf32_Word e_version; /* Object file version */
71  Elf32_Addr e_entry; /* Entry point virtual address */
72  Elf32_Off e_phoff; /* Program header table file offset */
73  Elf32_Off e_shoff; /* Section header table file offset */
74  Elf32_Word e_flags; /* Processor-specific flags */
75  Elf32_Half e_ehsize; /* ELF header size in bytes */
76  Elf32_Half e_phentsize; /* Program header table entry size */
77  Elf32_Half e_phnum; /* Program header table entry count */
78  Elf32_Half e_shentsize; /* Section header table entry size */
79  Elf32_Half e_shnum; /* Section header table entry count */
80  Elf32_Half e_shstrndx; /* Section header string table index */
81 } Elf32_Ehdr;
82 
83 typedef struct
84 {
85  unsigned char e_ident[EI_NIDENT]; /* Magic number and other info */
86  Elf64_Half e_type; /* Object file type */
87  Elf64_Half e_machine; /* Architecture */
88  Elf64_Word e_version; /* Object file version */
89  Elf64_Addr e_entry; /* Entry point virtual address */
90  Elf64_Off e_phoff; /* Program header table file offset */
91  Elf64_Off e_shoff; /* Section header table file offset */
92  Elf64_Word e_flags; /* Processor-specific flags */
93  Elf64_Half e_ehsize; /* ELF header size in bytes */
94  Elf64_Half e_phentsize; /* Program header table entry size */
95  Elf64_Half e_phnum; /* Program header table entry count */
96  Elf64_Half e_shentsize; /* Section header table entry size */
97  Elf64_Half e_shnum; /* Section header table entry count */
98  Elf64_Half e_shstrndx; /* Section header string table index */
99 } Elf64_Ehdr;

101 /* Fields in the e_ident array. The EI_* macros are indices into the
102  array. The macros under each EI_* macro are the values the byte
103  may have. */
104 
105 #define EI_MAG0 0 /* File identification byte 0 index */
106 #define ELFMAG0 0x7f /* Magic number byte 0 */
107 
108 #define EI_MAG1 1 /* File identification byte 1 index */
109 #define ELFMAG1 'E' /* Magic number byte 1 */
110 
111 #define EI_MAG2 2 /* File identification byte 2 index */
112 #define ELFMAG2 'L' /* Magic number byte 2 */
113 
114 #define EI_MAG3 3 /* File identification byte 3 index */
115 #define ELFMAG3 'F' /* Magic number byte 3 */
116 
117 /* Conglomeration of the identification bytes, for easy testing as a word. */
118 #define ELFMAG "\177ELF"
119 #define SELFMAG 4
120 
121 #define EI_CLASS 4 /* File class byte index */
122 #define ELFCLASSNONE 0 /* Invalid class */
123 #define ELFCLASS32 1 /* 32-bit objects */
124 #define ELFCLASS64 2 /* 64-bit objects */
125 #define ELFCLASSNUM 3
126 
127 #define EI_DATA 5 /* Data encoding byte index */
128 #define ELFDATANONE 0 /* Invalid data encoding */
129 #define ELFDATA2LSB 1 /* 2's complement, little endian */
130 #define ELFDATA2MSB 2 /* 2's complement, big endian */
131 #define ELFDATANUM 3
132 
133 #define EI_VERSION 6 /* File version byte index */
134  /* Value must be EV_CURRENT */
135 
136 #define EI_OSABI 7 /* OS ABI identification */
137 #define ELFOSABI_NONE 0 /* UNIX System V ABI */
138 #define ELFOSABI_SYSV 0 /* Alias. */
139 #define ELFOSABI_HPUX 1 /* HP-UX */
140 #define ELFOSABI_NETBSD 2 /* NetBSD. */
141 #define ELFOSABI_LINUX 3 /* Linux. */
142 #define ELFOSABI_SOLARIS 6 /* Sun Solaris. */
143 #define ELFOSABI_AIX 7 /* IBM AIX. */
144 #define ELFOSABI_IRIX 8 /* SGI Irix. */
145 #define ELFOSABI_FREEBSD 9 /* FreeBSD. */
146 #define ELFOSABI_TRU64 10 /* Compaq TRU64 UNIX. */
147 #define ELFOSABI_MODESTO 11 /* Novell Modesto. */
148 #define ELFOSABI_OPENBSD 12 /* OpenBSD. */
149 #define ELFOSABI_SIPAAKERNEL 13 /* SipaaKernel. */
150 #define ELFOSABI_ARM 97 /* ARM */
151 #define ELFOSABI_STANDALONE 255 /* Standalone (embedded) application */
152 
153 #define EI_ABIVERSION 8 /* ABI version */
154 
155 #define EI_PAD 9 /* Byte index of padding bytes */

161 #define ET_EXEC 2 /* Executable file */
162 #define ET_DYN 3 /* Shared object file */
163 #define ET_CORE 4 /* Core file */
164 #define ET_NUM 5 /* Number of defined types */
165 #define ET_LOOS 0xfe00 /* OS-specific range start */
166 #define ET_HIOS 0xfeff /* OS-specific range end */
167 #define ET_LOPROC 0xff00 /* Processor-specific range start */
168 #define ET_HIPROC 0xffff /* Processor-specific range end */

263 /* Section header. */
264 
265 typedef struct
266 {
267  Elf32_Word sh_name; /* Section name (string tbl index) */
268  Elf32_Word sh_type; /* Section type */
269  Elf32_Word sh_flags; /* Section flags */
270  Elf32_Addr sh_addr; /* Section virtual addr at execution */
271  Elf32_Off sh_offset; /* Section file offset */
272  Elf32_Word sh_size; /* Section size in bytes */
273  Elf32_Word sh_link; /* Link to another section */
274  Elf32_Word sh_info; /* Additional section information */
275  Elf32_Word sh_addralign; /* Section alignment */
276  Elf32_Word sh_entsize; /* Entry size if section holds table */
277 } Elf32_Shdr;
278 
279 typedef struct
280 {
281  Elf64_Word sh_name; /* Section name (string tbl index) */
282  Elf64_Word sh_type; /* Section type */
283  Elf64_Xword sh_flags; /* Section flags */
284  Elf64_Addr sh_addr; /* Section virtual addr at execution */
285  Elf64_Off sh_offset; /* Section file offset */
286  Elf64_Xword sh_size; /* Section size in bytes */
287  Elf64_Word sh_link; /* Link to another section */
288  Elf64_Word sh_info; /* Additional section information */
289  Elf64_Xword sh_addralign; /* Section alignment */
290  Elf64_Xword sh_entsize; /* Entry size if section holds table */
291 } Elf64_Shdr;

293 /* Special section indices. */
294 
295 #define SHN_UNDEF 0 /* Undefined section */
296 #define SHN_LORESERVE 0xff00 /* Start of reserved indices */
297 #define SHN_LOPROC 0xff00 /* Start of processor-specific */
298 #define SHN_BEFORE 0xff00 /* Order section before all others
299  (Solaris). */
300 #define SHN_AFTER 0xff01 /* Order section after all others
301  (Solaris). */
302 #define SHN_HIPROC 0xff1f /* End of processor-specific */
303 #define SHN_LOOS 0xff20 /* Start of OS-specific */
304 #define SHN_HIOS 0xff3f /* End of OS-specific */
305 #define SHN_ABS 0xfff1 /* Associated symbol is absolute */
306 #define SHN_COMMON 0xfff2 /* Associated symbol is common */
307 #define SHN_XINDEX 0xffff /* Index is in extra table. */
308 #define SHN_HIRESERVE 0xffff /* End of reserved indices */
309 
310 /* Legal values for sh_type (section type). */
311 
312 #define SHT_NULL 0 /* Section header table entry unused */
313 #define SHT_PROGBITS 1 /* Program data */
314 #define SHT_SYMTAB 2 /* Symbol table */
315 #define SHT_STRTAB 3 /* String table */
316 #define SHT_RELA 4 /* Relocation entries with addends */
317 #define SHT_HASH 5 /* Symbol hash table */
318 #define SHT_DYNAMIC 6 /* Dynamic linking information */
319 #define SHT_NOTE 7 /* Notes */
320 #define SHT_NOBITS 8 /* Program space with no data (bss) */
321 #define SHT_REL 9 /* Relocation entries, no addends */
322 #define SHT_SHLIB 10 /* Reserved */
323 #define SHT_DYNSYM 11 /* Dynamic linker symbol table */
324 #define SHT_INIT_ARRAY 14 /* Array of constructors */
325 #define SHT_FINI_ARRAY 15 /* Array of destructors */
326 #define SHT_PREINIT_ARRAY 16 /* Array of pre-constructors */
327 #define SHT_GROUP 17 /* Section group */
328 #define SHT_SYMTAB_SHNDX 18 /* Extended section indeces */
329 #define SHT_NUM 19 /* Number of defined types. */
330 #define SHT_LOOS 0x60000000 /* Start OS-specific. */
331 #define SHT_GNU_ATTRIBUTES 0x6ffffff5 /* Object attributes. */
332 #define SHT_GNU_HASH 0x6ffffff6 /* GNU-style hash table. */
333 #define SHT_GNU_LIBLIST 0x6ffffff7 /* Prelink library list */
334 #define SHT_CHECKSUM 0x6ffffff8 /* Checksum for DSO content. */
335 #define SHT_LOSUNW 0x6ffffffa /* Sun-specific low bound. */
336 #define SHT_SUNW_move 0x6ffffffa
337 #define SHT_SUNW_COMDAT 0x6ffffffb
338 #define SHT_SUNW_syminfo 0x6ffffffc
339 #define SHT_GNU_verdef 0x6ffffffd /* Version definition section. */
340 #define SHT_GNU_verneed 0x6ffffffe /* Version needs section. */
341 #define SHT_GNU_versym 0x6fffffff /* Version symbol table. */
342 #define SHT_HISUNW 0x6fffffff /* Sun-specific high bound. */
343 #define SHT_HIOS 0x6fffffff /* End OS-specific type */
344 #define SHT_LOPROC 0x70000000 /* Start of processor-specific */
345 #define SHT_HIPROC 0x7fffffff /* End of processor-specific */
346 #define SHT_LOUSER 0x80000000 /* Start of application-specific */
347 #define SHT_HIUSER 0x8fffffff /* End of application-specific */
348 
349 /* Legal values for sh_flags (section flags). */
350 
351 #define SHF_WRITE (1 << 0) /* Writable */
352 #define SHF_ALLOC (1 << 1) /* Occupies memory during execution */
353 #define SHF_EXECINSTR (1 << 2) /* Executable */
354 #define SHF_MERGE (1 << 4) /* Might be merged */
355 #define SHF_STRINGS (1 << 5) /* Contains nul-terminated strings */
356 #define SHF_INFO_LINK (1 << 6) /* `sh_info' contains SHT index */
357 #define SHF_LINK_ORDER (1 << 7) /* Preserve order after combining */
358 #define SHF_OS_NONCONFORMING (1 << 8) /* Non-standard OS specific handling
359  required */
360 #define SHF_GROUP (1 << 9) /* Section is member of a group. */
361 #define SHF_TLS (1 << 10) /* Section hold thread-local data. */
362 #define SHF_MASKOS 0x0ff00000 /* OS-specific. */
363 #define SHF_MASKPROC 0xf0000000 /* Processor-specific */
364 #define SHF_ORDERED (1 << 30) /* Special ordering requirement
365  (Solaris). */
366 #define SHF_EXCLUDE (1 << 31) /* Section is excluded unless
367  referenced or allocated (Solaris).*/
368 
369 /* Section group handling. */
370 #define GRP_COMDAT 0x1 /* Mark group as COMDAT. */
371 
372 /* Symbol table entry. */
373 
374 typedef struct
375 {
376  Elf32_Word st_name; /* Symbol name (string tbl index) */
377  Elf32_Addr st_value; /* Symbol value */
378  Elf32_Word st_size; /* Symbol size */
379  unsigned char st_info; /* Symbol type and binding */
380  unsigned char st_other; /* Symbol visibility */
381  Elf32_Section st_shndx; /* Section index */
382 } Elf32_Sym;
383 
384 typedef struct
385 {
386  Elf64_Word st_name; /* Symbol name (string tbl index) */
387  unsigned char st_info; /* Symbol type and binding */
388  unsigned char st_other; /* Symbol visibility */
389  Elf64_Section st_shndx; /* Section index */
390  Elf64_Addr st_value; /* Symbol value */
391  Elf64_Xword st_size; /* Symbol size */
392 } Elf64_Sym;

394 /* The syminfo section if available contains additional information about
395  every dynamic symbol. */
396 
397 typedef struct
398 {
399  Elf32_Half si_boundto; /* Direct bindings, symbol bound to */
400  Elf32_Half si_flags; /* Per symbol flags */
401 } Elf32_Syminfo;
402 
403 typedef struct
404 {
405  Elf64_Half si_boundto; /* Direct bindings, symbol bound to */
406  Elf64_Half si_flags; /* Per symbol flags */
407 } Elf64_Syminfo;
408 
409 /* Possible values for si_boundto. */
410 #define SYMINFO_BT_SELF 0xffff /* Symbol bound to self */
411 #define SYMINFO_BT_PARENT 0xfffe /* Symbol bound to parent */
412 #define SYMINFO_BT_LOWRESERVE 0xff00 /* Beginning of reserved entries */
413 
414 /* Possible bitmasks for si_flags. */
415 #define SYMINFO_FLG_DIRECT 0x0001 /* Direct bound symbol */
416 #define SYMINFO_FLG_PASSTHRU 0x0002 /* Pass-thru symbol for translator */
417 #define SYMINFO_FLG_COPY 0x0004 /* Symbol is a copy-reloc */
418 #define SYMINFO_FLG_LAZYLOAD 0x0008 /* Symbol bound to object to be lazy
419  loaded */
420 /* Syminfo version values. */
421 #define SYMINFO_NONE 0
422 #define SYMINFO_CURRENT 1
423 #define SYMINFO_NUM 2
424 
425 
426 /* How to extract and insert information held in the st_info field. */
427 
428 #define ELF32_ST_BIND(val) (((unsigned char) (val)) >> 4)
429 #define ELF32_ST_TYPE(val) ((val) & 0xf)
430 #define ELF32_ST_INFO(bind, type) (((bind) << 4) + ((type) & 0xf))
431 
432 /* Both Elf32_Sym and Elf64_Sym use the same one-byte st_info field. */
433 #define ELF64_ST_BIND(val) ELF32_ST_BIND (val)
434 #define ELF64_ST_TYPE(val) ELF32_ST_TYPE (val)
435 #define ELF64_ST_INFO(bind, type) ELF32_ST_INFO ((bind), (type))
436 
437 /* Legal values for ST_BIND subfield of st_info (symbol binding). */
438 
439 #define STB_LOCAL 0 /* Local symbol */
440 #define STB_GLOBAL 1 /* Global symbol */
441 #define STB_WEAK 2 /* Weak symbol */
442 #define STB_NUM 3 /* Number of defined types. */
443 #define STB_LOOS 10 /* Start of OS-specific */
444 #define STB_GNU_UNIQUE 10 /* Unique symbol. */
445 #define STB_HIOS 12 /* End of OS-specific */
446 #define STB_LOPROC 13 /* Start of processor-specific */
447 #define STB_HIPROC 15 /* End of processor-specific */
448 
449 /* Legal values for ST_TYPE subfield of st_info (symbol type). */
450 
451 #define STT_NOTYPE 0 /* Symbol type is unspecified */
452 #define STT_OBJECT 1 /* Symbol is a data object */
453 #define STT_FUNC 2 /* Symbol is a code object */
454 #define STT_SECTION 3 /* Symbol associated with a section */
455 #define STT_FILE 4 /* Symbol's name is file name */
456 #define STT_COMMON 5 /* Symbol is a common data object */
457 #define STT_TLS 6 /* Symbol is thread-local data object*/
458 #define STT_NUM 7 /* Number of defined types. */
459 #define STT_LOOS 10 /* Start of OS-specific */
460 #define STT_GNU_IFUNC 10 /* Symbol is indirect code object */
461 #define STT_HIOS 12 /* End of OS-specific */
462 #define STT_LOPROC 13 /* Start of processor-specific */
463 #define STT_HIPROC 15 /* End of processor-specific */
464 
465 
466 /* Symbol table indices are found in the hash buckets and chain table
467  of a symbol hash table section. This special index value indicates
468  the end of a chain, meaning no further symbols are found in that bucket. */
469 
470 #define STN_UNDEF 0 /* End of a chain. */
471 
472 
473 /* How to extract and insert information held in the st_other field. */
474 
475 #define ELF32_ST_VISIBILITY(o) ((o) & 0x03)
476 
477 /* For ELF64 the definitions are the same. */
478 #define ELF64_ST_VISIBILITY(o) ELF32_ST_VISIBILITY (o)
479 
480 /* Symbol visibility specification encoded in the st_other field. */
481 #define STV_DEFAULT 0 /* Default symbol visibility rules */
482 #define STV_INTERNAL 1 /* Processor specific hidden class */
483 #define STV_HIDDEN 2 /* Sym unavailable in other modules */
484 #define STV_PROTECTED 3 /* Not preemptible, not exported */

487 /* Relocation table entry without addend (in section of type SHT_REL). */
488 
489 typedef struct
490 {
491  Elf32_Addr r_offset; /* Address */
492  Elf32_Word r_info; /* Relocation type and symbol index */
493 } Elf32_Rel;
494 
495 /* I have seen two different definitions of the Elf64_Rel and
496  Elf64_Rela structures, so we'll leave them out until Novell (or
497  whoever) gets their act together. */
498 /* The following, at least, is used on Sparc v9, MIPS, and Alpha. */
499 
500 typedef struct
501 {
502  Elf64_Addr r_offset; /* Address */
503  Elf64_Xword r_info; /* Relocation type and symbol index */
504 } Elf64_Rel;
505 
506 /* Relocation table entry with addend (in section of type SHT_RELA). */
507 
508 typedef struct
509 {
510  Elf32_Addr r_offset; /* Address */
511  Elf32_Word r_info; /* Relocation type and symbol index */
512  Elf32_Sword r_addend; /* Addend */
513 } Elf32_Rela;
514 
515 typedef struct
516 {
517  Elf64_Addr r_offset; /* Address */
518  Elf64_Xword r_info; /* Relocation type and symbol index */
519  Elf64_Sxword r_addend; /* Addend */
520 } Elf64_Rela;
521 
522 /* How to extract and insert information held in the r_info field. */
523 
524 #define ELF32_R_SYM(val) ((val) >> 8)
525 #define ELF32_R_TYPE(val) ((val) & 0xff)
526 #define ELF32_R_INFO(sym, type) (((sym) << 8) + ((type) & 0xff))
527 
528 #define ELF64_R_SYM(i) ((i) >> 32)
529 #define ELF64_R_TYPE(i) ((i) & 0xffffffff)
530 #define ELF64_R_INFO(sym,type) ((((Elf64_Xword) (sym)) << 32) + (type))
531 
532 /* Program segment header. */
533 
534 typedef struct
535 {
536  Elf32_Word p_type; /* Segment type */

539  Elf32_Addr p_paddr; /* Segment physical address */
540  Elf32_Word p_filesz; /* Segment size in file */
541  Elf32_Word p_memsz; /* Segment size in memory */
542  Elf32_Word p_flags; /* Segment flags */
543  Elf32_Word p_align; /* Segment alignment */
544 } Elf32_Phdr;

671 #define DT_FINI_ARRAYSZ 28 /* Size in bytes of DT_FINI_ARRAY */

675 #define DT_PREINIT_ARRAY 32 /* Array with addresses of preinit fct*/
676 #define DT_PREINIT_ARRAYSZ 33 /* size in bytes of DT_PREINIT_ARRAY */
677 #define DT_NUM 34 /* Number used */
678 #define DT_LOOS 0x6000000d /* Start of OS-specific */

684 /* DT_* entries which fall between DT_VALRNGHI & DT_VALRNGLO use the
685  Dyn.d_un.d_val field of the Elf*_Dyn structure. This follows Sun's
686  approach. */
687 #define DT_VALRNGLO 0x6ffffd00
688 #define DT_GNU_PRELINKED 0x6ffffdf5 /* Prelinking timestamp */
689 #define DT_GNU_CONFLICTSZ 0x6ffffdf6 /* Size of conflict section */
690 #define DT_GNU_LIBLISTSZ 0x6ffffdf7 /* Size of library list */
691 #define DT_CHECKSUM 0x6ffffdf8
692 #define DT_PLTPADSZ 0x6ffffdf9
693 #define DT_MOVEENT 0x6ffffdfa
694 #define DT_MOVESZ 0x6ffffdfb

696 #define DT_POSFLAG_1 0x6ffffdfd /* Flags for DT_* entries, effecting
697  the following DT_* entry. */
698 #define DT_SYMINSZ 0x6ffffdfe /* Size of syminfo table (in bytes) */
699 #define DT_SYMINENT 0x6ffffdff /* Entry size of syminfo */
700 #define DT_VALRNGHI 0x6ffffdff
701 #define DT_VALTAGIDX(tag) (DT_VALRNGHI - (tag)) /* Reverse order! */
702 #define DT_VALNUM 12
703 
704 /* DT_* entries which fall between DT_ADDRRNGHI & DT_ADDRRNGLO use the
705  Dyn.d_un.d_ptr field of the Elf*_Dyn structure.
706 
707  If any adjustment is made to the ELF object after it has been
708  built these entries will need to be adjusted. */
709 #define DT_ADDRRNGLO 0x6ffffe00
710 #define DT_GNU_HASH 0x6ffffef5 /* GNU-style hash table. */
711 #define DT_TLSDESC_PLT 0x6ffffef6
712 #define DT_TLSDESC_GOT 0x6ffffef7
713 #define DT_GNU_CONFLICT 0x6ffffef8 /* Start of conflict section */
714 #define DT_GNU_LIBLIST 0x6ffffef9 /* Library list */
715 #define DT_CONFIG 0x6ffffefa /* Configuration information. */
716 #define DT_DEPAUDIT 0x6ffffefb /* Dependency auditing. */
717 #define DT_AUDIT 0x6ffffefc /* Object auditing. */
718 #define DT_PLTPAD 0x6ffffefd /* PLT padding. */
719 #define DT_MOVETAB 0x6ffffefe /* Move table. */
720 #define DT_SYMINFO 0x6ffffeff /* Syminfo table. */
721 #define DT_ADDRRNGHI 0x6ffffeff

723 #define DT_ADDRNUM 11

902 /* Auxiliary vector. */
903 
904 /* This vector is normally only used by the program interpreter. The
905  usual definition in an ABI supplement uses the name auxv_t. The
906  vector is not usually defined in a standard <elf.h> file, but it
907  can't hurt. We rename it to avoid conflicts. The sizes of these
908  types are an arrangement between the exec server and the program
909  interpreter, so we don't fully specify them here. */
910 
911 typedef struct
912 {
913  uint32_t a_type; /* Entry type */
914  union
915  {
916  uint32_t a_val; /* Integer value */
917  /* We use to have pointer elements added here. We cannot do that,
918  though, since it does not work when using 32-bit definitions
919  on 64-bit platforms and vice versa. */
920  } a_un;
921 } Elf32_auxv_t;
922 
923 typedef struct
924 {
925  uint64_t a_type; /* Entry type */
926  union
927  {
928  uint64_t a_val; /* Integer value */
929  /* We use to have pointer elements added here. We cannot do that,
930  though, since it does not work when using 32-bit definitions
931  on 64-bit platforms and vice versa. */
932  } a_un;
933 } Elf64_auxv_t;

935 /* Legal values for a_type (entry type). */
936 
937 #define AT_NULL 0 /* End of vector */
938 #define AT_IGNORE 1 /* Entry should be ignored */
939 #define AT_EXECFD 2 /* File descriptor of program */
940 #define AT_PHDR 3 /* Program headers for program */
941 #define AT_PHENT 4 /* Size of program header entry */
942 #define AT_PHNUM 5 /* Number of program headers */
943 #define AT_PAGESZ 6 /* System page size */
944 #define AT_BASE 7 /* Base address of interpreter */
945 #define AT_FLAGS 8 /* Flags */
946 #define AT_ENTRY 9 /* Entry point of program */
947 #define AT_NOTELF 10 /* Program is not ELF */
948 #define AT_UID 11 /* Real uid */
949 #define AT_EUID 12 /* Effective uid */
950 #define AT_GID 13 /* Real gid */
951 #define AT_EGID 14 /* Effective gid */
952 #define AT_CLKTCK 17 /* Frequency of times() */
953 
954 /* Some more special a_type values describing the hardware. */
955 #define AT_PLATFORM 15 /* String identifying platform. */
956 #define AT_HWCAP 16 /* Machine dependent hints about
957  processor capabilities. */
958 
959 /* This entry gives some information about the FPU initialization
960  performed by the kernel. */
961 #define AT_FPUCW 18 /* Used FPU control word. */

964 #define AT_DCACHEBSIZE 19 /* Data cache block size. */
965 #define AT_ICACHEBSIZE 20 /* Instruction cache block size. */
966 #define AT_UCACHEBSIZE 21 /* Unified cache block size. */
967

969  interpretation of the AUXV. Must be > 16. */
970 #define AT_IGNOREPPC 22 /* Entry should be ignored. */
971 
972 #define AT_SECURE 23 /* Boolean, was exec setuid-like? */
973 
974 #define AT_BASE_PLATFORM 24 /* String identifying real platforms.*/
975 
976 #define AT_RANDOM 25 /* Address of 16 random bytes. */

978 #define AT_EXECFN 31 /* Filename of executable. */

980 /* Pointer to the global system page used for system calls and other
981  nice things. */
982 #define AT_SYSINFO 32
983 #define AT_SYSINFO_EHDR 33

985 /* Shapes of the caches. Bits 0-3 contains associativity; bits 4-7 contains
986  log2 of line size; mask those to get cache size. */
987 #define AT_L1I_CACHESHAPE 34
988 #define AT_L1D_CACHESHAPE 35
989 #define AT_L2_CACHESHAPE 36
990 #define AT_L3_CACHESHAPE 37

1018 /* Defined types of notes for Solaris. */
1019 
1020 /* Value of descriptor (one word) is desired pagesize for the binary. */
1021 #define ELF_NOTE_PAGESIZE_HINT 1

1023 
1024 /* Defined note types for GNU systems. */
1025 
1026 /* ABI information. The descriptor consists of words:
1027  word 0: OS descriptor
1028  word 1: major version of the ABI
1029  word 2: minor version of the ABI
1030  word 3: subminor version of the ABI
1031 */
1032 #define NT_GNU_ABI_TAG 1
1033 #define ELF_NOTE_ABI NT_GNU_ABI_TAG /* Old name. */
1034

1036  NT_GNU_ABI_TAG note section entry. */
1037 #define ELF_NOTE_OS_LINUX 0
1038 #define ELF_NOTE_OS_GNU 1
1039 #define ELF_NOTE_OS_SOLARIS2 2
1040 #define ELF_NOTE_OS_FREEBSD 3
1041 
1042 /* Synthetic hwcap information. The descriptor begins with two words:
1043  word 0: number of entries
1044  word 1: bitmask of enabled entries
1045  Then follow variable-length entries, one byte followed by a
1046  '\0'-terminated hwcap name string. The byte gives the bit
1047  number to test if enabled, (1U << bit) & bitmask. */
1048 #define NT_GNU_HWCAP 2
1049

1051  The descriptor consists of any nonzero number of bytes. */
1052 #define NT_GNU_BUILD_ID 3
1053 
1054 /* Version note generated by GNU gold containing a version string. */
1055 #define NT_GNU_GOLD_VERSION 4

1448 /* Entries found in sections of type SHT_MIPS_GPTAB. */
1449 
1450 typedef union
1451 {
1452  struct
1453  {
1454  Elf32_Word gt_current_g_value; /* -G value used for compilation */
1455  Elf32_Word gt_unused; /* Not used */
1456  } gt_header; /* First entry in section */
1457  struct
1458  {
1459  Elf32_Word gt_g_value; /* If this value were used for -G */
1460  Elf32_Word gt_bytes; /* This many bytes would be used */
1461  } gt_entry; /* Subsequent entries in section */
1462 } Elf32_gptab;
1463 
1464 /* Entry found in sections of type SHT_MIPS_REGINFO. */
1465 
1466 typedef struct
1467 {
1468  Elf32_Word ri_gprmask; /* General registers used */
1469  Elf32_Word ri_cprmask[4]; /* Coprocessor registers used */
1470  Elf32_Sword ri_gp_value; /* $gp register value */
1471 } Elf32_RegInfo;
1472 
1473 /* Entries found in sections of type SHT_MIPS_OPTIONS. */
1474 
1475 typedef struct
1476 {
1477  unsigned char kind; /* Determines interpretation of the
1478  variable part of descriptor. */
1479  unsigned char size; /* Size of descriptor, including header. */
1480  Elf32_Section section; /* Section header index of section affected,
1481  0 for global options. */
1482  Elf32_Word info; /* Kind-specific information. */
1483 } Elf_Options;
1484 
1485 /* Values for `kind' field in Elf_Options. */
1486 
1487 #define ODK_NULL 0 /* Undefined. */
1488 #define ODK_REGINFO 1 /* Register usage information. */
1489 #define ODK_EXCEPTIONS 2 /* Exception processing options. */
1490 #define ODK_PAD 3 /* Section padding options. */
1491 #define ODK_HWPATCH 4 /* Hardware workarounds performed */
1492 #define ODK_FILL 5 /* record the fill value used by the linker. */

2621 #define R_X86_64_PC32 2 /* PC relative 32 bit signed */
2622 #define R_X86_64_GOT32 3 /* 32 bit GOT entry */
2623 #define R_X86_64_PLT32 4 /* 32 bit PLT address */
2624 #define R_X86_64_COPY 5 /* Copy symbol at runtime */
2625 #define R_X86_64_GLOB_DAT 6 /* Create GOT entry */
2626 #define R_X86_64_JUMP_SLOT 7 /* Create PLT entry */
2627 #define R_X86_64_RELATIVE 8 /* Adjust by program base */
2628 #define R_X86_64_GOTPCREL 9 /* 32 bit signed PC relative
2629  offset to GOT */
2630 #define R_X86_64_32 10 /* Direct 32 bit zero extended */
2631 #define R_X86_64_32S 11 /* Direct 32 bit sign extended */
2632 #define R_X86_64_16 12 /* Direct 16 bit zero extended */
2633 #define R_X86_64_PC16 13 /* 16 bit sign extended pc relative */
2634 #define R_X86_64_8 14 /* Direct 8 bit sign extended */
2635 #define R_X86_64_PC8 15 /* 8 bit sign extended pc relative */
2636 #define R_X86_64_DTPMOD64 16 /* ID of module containing symbol */
2637 #define R_X86_64_DTPOFF64 17 /* Offset in module's TLS block */
2638 #define R_X86_64_TPOFF64 18 /* Offset in initial TLS block */
2639 #define R_X86_64_TLSGD 19 /* 32 bit signed PC relative offset
2640  to two GOT entries for GD symbol */
2641 #define R_X86_64_TLSLD 20 /* 32 bit signed PC relative offset
2642  to two GOT entries for LD symbol */
2643 #define R_X86_64_DTPOFF32 21 /* Offset in TLS block */
2644 #define R_X86_64_GOTTPOFF 22 /* 32 bit signed PC relative offset
2645  to GOT entry for IE symbol */
2646 #define R_X86_64_TPOFF32 23 /* Offset in initial TLS block */
2647 #define R_X86_64_PC64 24 /* PC relative 64 bit */
2648 #define R_X86_64_GOTOFF64 25 /* 64 bit offset to GOT */
2649 #define R_X86_64_GOTPC32 26 /* 32 bit signed pc relative
2650  offset to GOT */
2651 /* 27 .. 33 */
2652 #define R_X86_64_GOTPC32_TLSDESC 34 /* GOT offset for TLS descriptor. */
2653 #define R_X86_64_TLSDESC_CALL 35 /* Marker for call through TLS
2654  descriptor. */
2655 #define R_X86_64_TLSDESC 36 /* TLS descriptor. */
2656 #define R_X86_64_IRELATIVE 37 /* Adjust indirectly by program base */
2657 
2658 #define R_X86_64_NUM 38

2778 /* Type for a 16-bit quantity. */

2780 typedef uint16_t Elf64_Half;

2783 typedef uint32_t Elf32_Word;
2784 typedef int32_t Elf32_Sword;
2785 typedef uint32_t Elf64_Word;
2786 typedef int32_t Elf64_Sword;

2790 typedef int64_t Elf32_Sxword;
2791 typedef uint64_t Elf64_Xword;
2792 typedef int64_t Elf64_Sxword;

2800 typedef uint64_t Elf64_Off;

2811 /* The ELF file header. This appears at the start of every ELF file. */
2812 
2813 #define EI_NIDENT (16)
2814 
2815 typedef struct
2816 {
2817  unsigned char e_ident[EI_NIDENT]; /* Magic number and other info */
2818  Elf32_Half e_type; /* Object file type */
2819  Elf32_Half e_machine; /* Architecture */
2820  Elf32_Word e_version; /* Object file version */
2821  Elf32_Addr e_entry; /* Entry point virtual address */
2822  Elf32_Off e_phoff; /* Program header table file offset */
2823  Elf32_Off e_shoff; /* Section header table file offset */
2824  Elf32_Word e_flags; /* Processor-specific flags */
2825  Elf32_Half e_ehsize; /* ELF header size in bytes */
2826  Elf32_Half e_phentsize; /* Program header table entry size */
2827  Elf32_Half e_phnum; /* Program header table entry count */
2828  Elf32_Half e_shentsize; /* Section header table entry size */
2829  Elf32_Half e_shnum; /* Section header table entry count */
2830  Elf32_Half e_shstrndx; /* Section header string table index */
2831 } Elf32_Ehdr;
2832 
2833 typedef struct
2834 {
2835  unsigned char e_ident[EI_NIDENT]; /* Magic number and other info */
2836  Elf64_Half e_type; /* Object file type */
2837  Elf64_Half e_machine; /* Architecture */
2838  Elf64_Word e_version; /* Object file version */
2839  Elf64_Addr e_entry; /* Entry point virtual address */
2840  Elf64_Off e_phoff; /* Program header table file offset */
2841  Elf64_Off e_shoff; /* Section header table file offset */
2842  Elf64_Word e_flags; /* Processor-specific flags */
2843  Elf64_Half e_ehsize; /* ELF header size in bytes */
2844  Elf64_Half e_phentsize; /* Program header table entry size */
2845  Elf64_Half e_phnum; /* Program header table entry count */
2846  Elf64_Half e_shentsize; /* Section header table entry size */
2847  Elf64_Half e_shnum; /* Section header table entry count */
2848  Elf64_Half e_shstrndx; /* Section header string table index */
2849 } Elf64_Ehdr;

3044 #define SHN_UNDEF 0 /* Undefined section */
3045 #define SHN_LORESERVE 0xff00 /* Start of reserved indices */
3046 #define SHN_LOPROC 0xff00 /* Start of processor-specific */
3047 #define SHN_BEFORE 0xff00 /* Order section before all others
3048  (Solaris). */
3049 #define SHN_AFTER 0xff01 /* Order section after all others
3050  (Solaris). */

3052 #define SHN_LOOS 0xff20 /* Start of OS-specific */
3053 #define SHN_HIOS 0xff3f /* End of OS-specific */
3054 #define SHN_ABS 0xfff1 /* Associated symbol is absolute */
3055 #define SHN_COMMON 0xfff2 /* Associated symbol is common */
3056 #define SHN_XINDEX 0xffff /* Index is in extra table. */
3057 #define SHN_HIRESERVE 0xffff /* End of reserved indices */

3063 #define SHT_SYMTAB 2 /* Symbol table */
3064 #define SHT_STRTAB 3 /* String table */
3065 #define SHT_RELA 4 /* Relocation entries with addends */
3066 #define SHT_HASH 5 /* Symbol hash table */

3068 #define SHT_NOTE 7 /* Notes */
3069 #define SHT_NOBITS 8 /* Program space with no data (bss) */
3070 #define SHT_REL 9 /* Relocation entries, no addends */
3071 #define SHT_SHLIB 10 /* Reserved */

3651 /* Auxiliary vector. */
3652 
3653 /* This vector is normally only used by the program interpreter. The
3654  usual definition in an ABI supplement uses the name auxv_t. The
3655  vector is not usually defined in a standard <elf.h> file, but it
3656  can't hurt. We rename it to avoid conflicts. The sizes of these
3657  types are an arrangement between the exec server and the program
3658  interpreter, so we don't fully specify them here. */
3659 
3660 typedef struct
3661 {
3662  uint32_t a_type; /* Entry type */
3663  union
3664  {
3665  uint32_t a_val; /* Integer value */
3666  /* We use to have pointer elements added here. We cannot do that,
3667  though, since it does not work when using 32-bit definitions
3668  on 64-bit platforms and vice versa. */
3669  } a_un;
3670 } Elf32_auxv_t;
3671 
3672 typedef struct
3673 {
3674  uint64_t a_type; /* Entry type */
3675  union
3676  {
3677  uint64_t a_val; /* Integer value */
3678  /* We use to have pointer elements added here. We cannot do that,
3679  though, since it does not work when using 32-bit definitions
3680  on 64-bit platforms and vice versa. */
3681  } a_un;
3682 } Elf64_auxv_t;

3691 #define AT_PHNUM 5 /* Number of program headers */

3694 #define AT_FLAGS 8 /* Flags */

3698 #define AT_EUID 12 /* Effective uid */
